  "prompt": "Why do airplanes use two-pronged headphones?",
  "response": "Airplanes use two-pronged headphones primarily for historical and compatibility reasons. The standard two-prong audio jack was common in older aircraft entertainment systems and has remained in use due to several factors:\n\n1. Durability: The two-pronged design is more robust and less prone to damage compared to modern single-prong headphone jacks.\n\n2. Compatibility: Many aircraft still use older entertainment systems that were designed with this standard connector.\n\n3. Cost-effectiveness: Retrofitting entire fleets with new audio systems would be expensive, so airlines continue to use the existing two-pronged design.\n\n4. Noise-canceling: Some airline headphones are specifically designed to provide better noise reduction in a noisy cabin environment.\n\nMost airlines provide complimentary two-pronged headphones, but passengers can also purchase adapters to use their own standard headphones with the aircraft's audio system.",
